I think it might be simpler to track a deadline than a timeout on the status message.

In showStatusMessage, instead of recording statusMessageDuration, we would record statusMessageDeadline of when the message should stop showing

```go
func (r *treeRenderer) showStatusMessage(msg string, duration time.Duration) {
  // ...
  r.statusMessageDeadline = time.Now().Add(duration)
}

Then, if a status message was printed below around the "enforce timeout" bit:

```go
if statusMessage != "" {
  if time.Until(r.statusMessageDeadline) <= 0 {
    r.statusMessage, r.statusMessageDeadline = "", time.Time{}
  }
}
```

This will be a lot cheaper than tracking the time since each frame render (which, albeit, isn't that expensive) because it will hit time.Now and friends only if there was a status message to print in the first place—which is going to be rare.

